data.body:
I finally had a deeper look of the code, it seems that by doing this way, we are duplicating twice the buffers. Indeed, look at [TypedArray MDN Documentation](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/TypedArray). When calling the following code, it seems to already copy the array.

```javascript
function Int8BufferAttribute( array, itemSize ) {

	BufferAttribute.call( this, new Int8Array( array ), itemSize );

}
```

> When called with a typedArray argument, which can be an object of any of the typed array types (such as Int32Array), the typedArray gets copied into a new typed array. Each value in typedArray is converted to the corresponding type of the constructor before being copied into the new array. Then length of the new typedArray object will be same of length of the typedArray argument.

Then by calling copy on the clone method, we are duplicating the array a second time.

```javascript
copy: function ( source ) {

	this.array = new source.array.constructor( source.array ); // Second duplication occurs here
	this.itemSize = source.itemSize;
	this.count = source.count;
	this.normalized = source.normalized;

	this.dynamic = source.dynamic;

	return this;

},
```

So, if I'm right, and if performances really matters on this part of the code, we should modify clone method like following proposition to avoid double duplication :
```javascript
clone: function () {

        var clone = new this.constructor( this.array, this.itemSize );
        clone.normalized = this.normalized;
        clone.dynamic = this.dynamic;
	return clone;

}
```
Instead of :
```javascript
clone: function () {

	return new this.constructor( this.array, this.itemSize ).copy( this );

}
```

What do you think of it?
